(* Combinator covers only the four *explicit* combinators written as punctuation.
   The descendant combinator is intentionally absent.

   Per the CSS spec, the descendant combinator is "one or more CSS whitespace
   characters — the space character and/or carriage return, form feed, newline,
   or tab — between two selectors in the absence of another combinator."
   Those whitespace characters may contain any number of CSS comments.

   Because the parser (gluon) skips whitespace and block comments automatically
   between syntactic productions, the descendant relationship does not need an
   explicit token. It is encoded implicitly in selector.ebnf: wherever
   ComplexSelector, NestedComplexSelector, or ComplexSelectorNoPe writes

       { [ Combinator ] , CompoundSelector }

   an absent Combinator — with the whitespace already consumed by the parser —
   represents a descendant relationship. An explicit Combinator present at that
   position represents child (>), next-sibling (+), subsequent-sibling (~), or
   column (||).

   This matches the CSS spec's definition exactly: the descendant combinator is
   whitespace *in the absence of another combinator*, not a distinct token. *)

Combinator = ChildCombinator | ColumnCombinator | NextSiblingCombinator | SubsequentSiblingCombinator ;

ChildCombinator = greater_than_sign_symbol ;

ColumnCombinator = double_vertical_line_symbol ;

NextSiblingCombinator = plus_sign_symbol ;

SubsequentSiblingCombinator = tilde_symbol ;